%N A393445 Primes p at which A373813 increases.
%C A393445 The first 143 terms have been computed and proved optimal using the exact solver described in the Links. The largest gap between consecutive terms is 111 nonawkward primes, occurring between a(69)=3301 and a(70)=4211, corresponding to the plateau at f(n)=69 for n=465..575 in A373813. A notable earlier plateau is the 40-step run at f=14 (n=60..99), ended by the awkward prime a(15)=541. - _Jesper Gran Mikkelsen_, May 10 2026
%H A393445 Jesper Gran Mikkelsen, <a href="/A393445/b393445.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..143</a>
%H A393445 Brady Haran and N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VFoIPlUalRY">Awkward Primes</a>, YouTube Numberphile video, 2026.
%H A393445 Jesper Gran Mikkelsen, <a href="https://github.com/jespergran98/prime-line-cover">Prime Line Cover solver</a>, GitHub.
%H A393445 Jesper Gran Mikkelsen, <a href="https://prime-line-cover.vercel.app">Interactive demo</a> (JavaScript port of the solver, runs in browser).
%H A393445 Jesper Gran Mikkelsen, <a href="https://prime-line-cover.vercel.app/pdf_exact_solver_for_minimum_line_cover_of_prime_points.pdf">An Exact Solver for the Minimum Line Cover of Prime-Indexed Points</a>, preprint, 2026.
%H A393445 Jesper Gran Mikkelsen, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20096556">Source code and certified results for n = 1..1024</a>, Zenodo, 2026.
%F A393445 a(n) = A000040(Sum_{i=1..n} A373814(i)). - _Gregory Morse_, Apr 07 2026
%e A393445 13 is a term because whereas all of 2, 3, 5, 7, and 11 can be covered by A373813(5) = 2 straight lines, an additional line is needed to also cover 13.
%o A393445 (C++) // Jesper Gran Mikkelsen, https://github.com/jespergran98/prime-line-cover
%Y A393445 Cf. A373813, A373814, A393446.
%K A393445 nonn,changed
%O A393445 1,1
%A A393445 _N. J. A. Sloane_, Mar 02 2026, following a suggestion from Brady Haran, who suggests these might be called "awkward" primes, since they require an additional straight line to cover them.
